[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":7,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/qztAf.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22628,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22628/arboviral","reputation":595,"display_name":"arboviral"},"score":0,"post_id":44201,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461577625,"comment_id":79856,"body":"+1 for the answer to the first part of the question, but the second needs work; differences in height due to sex are probably primarily due to development rather than genetics (males and females are fairly well-mixed populations...). This paper describes one developmental mechanism (sex-based differences in GH-dependent STAT5b regulation of IGF-I expression): <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15506072\" rel=\"nofollow\">ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15506072<\/a>. It also discusses selective pressures for sexual dimorphism in humans versus other species, which could be another part of the answer to the &quot;reasons&quot; part of the question."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461563130,"creation_date":1457725806,"body":"<p><strong>Are males taller than females?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Best data I could find come from the <a href=\"https://www.census.gov/library/publications/1999/compendia/statab/119ed.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Statistical Abstract of the United States (1999) > Section 3<\/a>. Here is a table reporting the percentage of the male and female population which height is lower than a given threshold<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/teuub.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/teuub.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Note that this censing was done among students in US Universities and is therefore not representative of the whole world or even the whole country.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Does height follows a bimodal distribution?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Difference in height between males and females is often used as a classical example in introductory statistic class to exemplify a bimodal distribution as seen in this picture<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/VBeVM.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/VBeVM.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>and on these (a priori fake) data<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ZlOKhm.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ZlOKhm.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>However, <a href=\"http://amstat.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1198/00031300265\" rel=\"nofollow\">Schilling et al. 2002<\/a> argued that <strong>while the difference in mean height between gender is real, this difference is too small relatively to the variance in height within each gender to be clearly depicted on a graph<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Note that I found <a href=\"https://sugarandslugs.wordpress.com/2011/02/13/sex-differences/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this non-peer-reviewed paper<\/a> who shows real data that display a truly bimodal distribution of height.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ekqFqm.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ekqFqm.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Genetics of height<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>The question <code>why are they taller?<\/code> is very broad. I will just focus to give you some hints about the genetics of height in humans. First you want to make sure you understand the <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42273/why-is-a-heritability-coefficient-not-an-index-of-how-genetic-something-is\">concept of heritability<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://ac.els-cdn.com/S1570677X09000793/1-s2.0-S1570677X09000793-main.pdf?_tid=b23cd550-e7bc-11e5-aee5-00000aab0f6c&amp;acdnat=1457723513_e3c43d12b238a90fea7a4b1d36defda8\" rel=\"nofollow\">Evoy and Vissher 2009<\/a> reports a heritability coefficient of 0.8. This estimate that is impressively high a few phenotypic traits have such high heritability. They also review articles discussing 50 loci are are correlated with variation in height. However, these loci are not sufficient to explain the whole heritability observed (common missing heritability issue). <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/ng/journal/v42/n7/pdf/ng.608.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Yang et al. 2010<\/a> provide evidence that the remaining heritability is due to incomplete linkage\ndisequilibrium between causal variants and loci of weak effects. In short, height is a highly polygenic trait.<\/p>\n","answer_id":44201,"question_id":44199,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1461563130}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44199/are-males-taller-than-females","migrated_from":{"other_site":{"icon_url":"http://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/health/img/apple-touch-icon.png","audience":"medical specialists, students, dietitians, and anyone with health-related questions","favicon_url":"http://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/health/img/favicon.ico","site_type":"main_site","logo_url":"http://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/health/img/logo.png","api_site_parameter":"health","open_beta_date":1429747200,"site_state":"open_beta","related_sites":[{"site_url":"http://meta.health.stackexchange.com","api_site_parameter":"meta.health","name":"Health Meta Stack Exchange","relation":"meta"},{"site_url":"http://chat.stackexchange.com?tab=site&host=health.stackexchange.com","name":"Chat Stack Exchange","relation":"chat"}],"closed_beta_date":1427760000,"styling":{"tag_background_color":"#FFF","link_color":"#0077CC","tag_foreground_color":"#000"},"site_url":"http://health.stackexchange.com","name":"Health"},"on_date":1457719900,"question_id":5094},"last_activity_date":1461563130,"creation_date":1457697891,"answer_count":1,"title":"Are males taller than females?","body":"