morphism has to do with the phenotype.<\/p>\n\n<p>Most loci (=position in the genome) that contain more than one allele (=genetic variant) have no effect on the phenotype. So multiple allelism does not necessarily yield to phenotypic polymorphism.<\/p>\n\n<p>On the other hand, plenty of phenotypic variation in a population is due to environmental variation (including what an individual eats) and not to genetic variation. So phenotypic polymorphism is not necessarily caused by a case of multiple allelism.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45576,"question_id":44930,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44930/what-is-the-difference-between-multiple-allelism-and-polymorphism","last_activity_date":1461562927,"creation_date":1459904780,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the difference between multiple allelism and polymorphism?","body":"<p>Multiple allelism is defined as \"the existence of more than two alleles of the same gene within a population.\" Polymorphism is \"the occurrence of more than two distinct phenotypes of a trait in a population.\" Both definitions are according to Scott Freeman's <em>Biological Science<\/em> textbook. I don't really understand the difference---unless it means that two alleles may not result in two different phenotypes?<\/p>\n\n<p>Additionally, another definition of polymorphism also in the textbook was \"the existence of more than one allele at a certain genetic locus.\" What does this mean? I was under the impression that all genes had at least two alleles.<\/p>\n","question_id":44930,"tags":["genetics"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":45576,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":52,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1460082861},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-on6yuwN5JEs/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAABU/8oD_p798mqw/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":16460,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16460/sanjukta-ghosh","reputation":432,"display_name":"Sanjukta Gho