- and dideoxy-ribose, and that of the phospho-diester bond in DNA. (Learning them would be good.). Then the answer to the question will become obvious to you and you will have learnt something."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Fdh9e.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23258,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23258/scient","reputation":71,"display_name":"SciEnt"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461555881,"creation_date":1461555881,"body":"<p>It is false, because DNA synthesis occurs via DNA polymerase,5' to 3'<\/p>\n\n<p>By hydrolyzing activated nucleotides together. This occurs by nucleophilic attack of 3'-OH, of the last nucleotide in sequence, on alpha phosphate of a corresponding nucleotide triphosphates.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45570,"question_id":45565,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45565/true-or-false-dideoxynucleotide-sequence-analysis-question","last_activity_date":1461555881,"creation_date":1461533801,"answer_count":1,"title":"True or False: Dideoxynucleotide sequence analysis Question","body":"<p>Dideoxynucleotide sequence analysis is a template-directed method that makes use of chain terminators that stop DNA synthesis because they lack a 2'OH group. <\/p>\n\n<p>True or false?<\/p>\n\n<p>Apparently the answer is false, but I think this is true because dont dideoxynucleotide sequences stop DNA synthesis due to a lack of an OH group on a 2' and 3' group?<\/p>\n","question_id":45565,"tags":["dna"],"score":-1,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":false,"view_count":31,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/97d9b8b0b2cbf058380849f34a05cc34?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21283,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21283/green","reputation":173,"display_name":"Green"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/XdJ9g.jpg?s=128&g=1","u