35ad9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3037,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3037/mart","reputation":324,"display_name":"mart","accept_rate":55},"score":0,"post_id":42645,"edited":false,"creation_date":1453732144,"comment_id":73405,"body":"fwiw, english wikipedia on crocodilia states &quot;10-20% of what a lion needs&quot; witht this paywalled source: <a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1986.tb01518.x/abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\">onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1986.tb01518.x/&hellip;<\/a> someone with access could use this maybe?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19493,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19493/david-blomstrom","reputation":1247,"display_name":"David Blomstrom"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1453768163,"creation_date":1453768163,"body":"<p>It's only a partial answer, but a Nile crocodile can eat up to half its body weight at a sitting, according to <a href=\"http://animals.nationalgeographic.com/animals/reptiles/nile-crocodile/\" rel=\"nofollow\">National Geographic<\/a>. Since few freshwater fish weigh half as much as a crocodile, we can probably assume these croc feasts occur when they're able to ambush ungulates (e.g. zebras and antelope).<\/p>\n\n<p>So one guess is that a crocodile feasts on ungulates about fifty times a year, though its normal diet is fish. Of course, I could be wrong - perhaps five fish caught in the space of an hour are considered a full meal as well.<\/p>\n\n<p>I never knew crocodilians ate fruit. (The link you provided doesn't mention fruit, by the way.) But <a href=\"http://www.livescience.com/39198-crocodiles-alligators-eat-fruit.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">this article<\/a> says they can eat \"large quantities\" of fruit, suggesting they're looking for more than 