 although some cells, such as Drosophila embryos (discussed later) and vertebrate osteoclasts (discussed in Chapter 22), undergo mitosis without cytokinesis and become multinucleate. Cytokinesis begins in anaphase and ends in telophase, reaching completion as the next interphase begins.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The mouse-over definition of cytokinesis there is:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Division of the cytoplasm of a plant or animal cell into two, as distinct from the division of its nucleus (which is mitosis)<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":10332,"question_id":10325,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/10325/does-mitosis-include-cytokinesis","last_activity_date":1461534937,"creation_date":1378570284,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does mitosis include cytokinesis?","body":"<p>I found that some books include cytokinesis within mitosis, but some other books I have referred to include only the dividing of the nucleus as mitosis and do not include cytokinesis.<\/p>\n\n<p>Can anyone help me out? Please include a source in your answer.<\/p>\n","question_id":10325,"tags":["terminology","mitosis","cytokinesis"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":10332,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1391,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1383237576},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8dc4b4ce15a604368dc45b0185c96940?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23464,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23464/genomecheck","reputation":1,"display_name":"genomecheck"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45564/what-information-do-bipolar-cells-encode","last_activity_date":1461525168,"creation_date":1461525168,"answer_count":0,"title":"What information do bipolar cells encode?","body":"<p>Short version: I don't see what information on-centre bipolar cells are actually capturing.<\/p>\n\n<p>Longer:<\/p>\n\n<p>Actually, the question could be extended to on-centre retinal cells as well, but I'll focus on bipolar cells for now.<\/p>\n\n<p>On-centre cells will fire when a spot of light hits the centre of their receptive fields and doesn't touch their surround, off-centres are the reverse (light in the centre is inhibitory, surround is excitatory).<\/p>\n\n<p>Here's an over-simplified illustration that I made, red is hyperpolarized (excited), blue is hypopolarized (inhibited). Let's pretend that horizontal cell effects have already happened, and ignoring overlapping receptive fields for simplicity.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Dzb6v.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Dzb6v.png\" alt=\"Here&#39;s an over-simplified illustration that I made, red is hyperpolarized (excited), blue is hypopolarized (inhibited)\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>So my question is, if off-centre cells would be useful to highlight contrasts like edges (as I understand it, though eventually edges get detected further down in the complex cells), what are on-centre bipolar cells used for?<\/p>\n\n<p>From my perspective it looks like they'd be good for single points in light which are small enough to hit the small number of rods that encompass the centre of a receptive field but not hit the surround. But when would this ever be the case? The centre of a receptive field would be incredibly tiny given the large number of rods in say the fovea (though, granted, maybe on-centre cells become more important in the periphery?).<\/p>\n\n<p>One source:\n<a href=\"http://thebrain.mcgill.ca/flash/a/a_02/a_02_cl/a_02_cl_vis/a_02_cl_vis.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://thebrain.mcgill.ca/flash/a/a_02/a_02_cl/a_02_cl_vis/a_02_cl_vis.html<\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":45564,"tags":["cell-biology","neuroscience","neurophysiology","neuroanatomy","cell-signaling"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":15,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/71e3da221ac29ea8a2ffeba372820da4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user