 provide resistance against malaria.<\/p>\n\n<p>The key thing about these diseases is that it is the heterozygote that is protected from malaria and only suffers mildly from the disease (or may even show no symptoms) The homozygote, in contrast, is generally badly effected and may have a poor life expectancy. The explanation is that in the heterozygote the amount of functional haemoglobin is reduced to half, but that is sufficient in normal circumstances. (Sickle cell anaemia is more complex, but in principle similar.) However for <a href=\"https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/04/110428123931.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">reasons<\/a> that are more complex than one might expect, the pathogenicity of the parasite is decreased in such individuals.<\/p>\n\n<p>As you will be aware, the haemoglobin molecule in adult humans is made up of two alpha-chains and two beta-chains, each of which can bind an oxygen molecule. Why then are most haemoglobinopathies due to mutations involving the beta-chain? One answer may be that <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fetal_hemoglobin\" rel=\"nofollow\">foetal haemoglobin<\/a> has a different structure \u2014 two alpha-chains and two gamma-chains. (This shifts its oxygen affinity in a manner appropriate for its relation between foetal and maternal circulations.) Hence mutations in alpha-globin could lead to still births, and in fact these are prevalent in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha-thalassemia\" rel=\"nofollow\">alpha-thalassaemia<\/a>. As the foetal haemoglobin lacks beta-chains, this problem does not arise in beta-haemoglobinopathies.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Postscript<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>As a native of Northern Europe, I had tended to think of the problem of thalassaemia in Southern Europe as something that had disappeared long ago. This idea was dispelled last summer when I chanced on a thalassaemia centre in Ferrara in Italy. The upper plaque shown is a tribute to a doctor at the centre, and the second plaque would probably be expressed in English as \u201cCity of Ferrara Genetic Counselling Clinic for Thalassaemia\u201d. (\u2018Morbo di Cooley\u2019 is an Italian alternative to \u2018talassemia\u2019.)<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/M4wNr.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/M4wNr.jpg\" alt=\"Thalassaemia cliic in Ferrara, Italy\"><\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":45549,"question_id":45536,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1461495595}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45536/why-have-multiple-alleles-for-beta-chains-evolved-in-certain-parts-of-the-world","last_activity_date":1461507842,"creation_date":1461442646,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why have multiple alleles for beta chains evolved in certain parts of the world?","body":"<p>I believe that this could be because individuals may have had interactions with a parasite, for example Malaria, that caused changes resulting in different beta chains.<\/p>\n\n<p>Can anyone explain this more clearly?<\/p>\n","question_id":45536,"tags":["evolution","proteins","hematology","medicine","parasitology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"unclear what you're asking","is_answered":false,"view_count":22,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1461507842},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a1bbe65cd18cb6a4b1173464ddb9ab9d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":23455,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23455/ayesha-ali","reputation":1,"display_name":"ayesha ali"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":45556,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461557778,"comment_id":79829,"body":"They keep it refrigerated."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45556/how-to-increase-the-shelf-life-of-yogurt","last_