,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":45542,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461567267,"comment_id":79844,"body":"@mgkrebbs whoever named these proteins named the chains with similar greek letters for compatibility. I don&#39;t think they were named based on the chains they have. See the linked post. I think the answer there explains the possible origin of these names."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461476620,"creation_date":1461476620,"body":"<p>The letter suffix in the name or abbreviation of an <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antibody\" rel=\"nofollow\">immunoglobulin<\/a> specifies which type of \"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immunoglobulin_heavy_chain\" rel=\"nofollow\">heavy chain<\/a>\" the immunoglobin contains. The heavy chain is the large polypeptide (amino acid chain) found in the antibody.  In mammals there are five different classes or types of heavy chains, and these types are given Greek letters to differentiate them.<\/p>\n\n<p>As <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antibody#Isotypes\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia says<\/a>,  <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The different suffixes of the antibody isotypes denote the different\n  types of heavy chains the antibody contains, with each heavy chain\n  class named alphabetically: α, γ, δ, ε, and μ. This gives rise to IgA,\n  IgG, IgD, IgE, and IgM, respectively.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Thus the Ig suffix letter is the Roman letter corresponding to the equivalent Greek letter of the heavy chain that Ig contains.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45542,"question_id":45540,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45540/what-is-a-in-iga","last_activity_date":1461476620,"creation_date":1461472998,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is A in IgA?","body":"<p>What is the significance of letter A in immunoglobulinA?<\/p>\n\n<p>What are the significance of other letters D, M , G, E in diffeternt types of antibodies?<\/p>\n","question_id":45540,"tags":["antibody"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":45542,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"duplicate","is_answered":true,"view_count":131,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/265a636403a666dfd073e77e24ef8651?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21363,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21363/biology-nerd","reputation":4,"display_name":"Biology nerd"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":45541,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461481936,"comment_id":79767,"body":"Amy sources to your claim?  I&#39;ve never heard of using bacteria against cancer?!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":45541,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461509033,"comment_id":79791,"body":"@Christiaan I actually interviewed recently at a company that&#39;s doing just that. It&#39;s really interesting."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/LBnjL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22415,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22415/graham-chiu","reputation":254,"display_name":"Graham Chiu"},"score":0,"post_id":45541,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461550827,"comment_id":79827,"body":"Is OP talking about Coley&#39;s toxins? <a href=\"http://www.cancerresearchuk