ld be their descendants. Similarly, during a bottleneck a few individuals give rise to the entire population. Now, if you take generation-0 and any later generation-Y, compared to some generation-X and generation-Y (X&lt;Y) then there the lineage would be intact for the former. Plus there are other factors such as fitness of the starter population."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d79c7576fd1035d7c9a89cd25a44295b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17204,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17204/nick","reputation":201,"display_name":"Nick"},"score":0,"post_id":36715,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1439201856,"comment_id":61396,"body":"@March Ho The percentage of the people living at a time point before the bottleneck who have a living lineage would still be lower than for the generations afterwards. I know that a scenario can be constructed in which this is not strictly true but, generally, the rule holds for realistic bottlenecks - at least in species with birth rate not much greater than those of humans. However this point is a bit tangential to what I asked."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":2,"post_id":36715,"edited":false,"creation_date":1439325315,"comment_id":61492,"body":"Interesting question +1. One can calculate such things using Coalescent Theory but the issue is that it assumes constant effective population size which is obviously very wrong for England. The Coalescence should have very long branches, much longer than expected from constant effective population size. I don&#39;t think there is an analytical method for dealing with growing population size. Also, the descendents went through several bottlenecks and rapid expansion so it definitely is not an easy case. I don&#39;t think that theory can help here, one will need to analyze data to answer this question."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-JU-6fQpM_Xs/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAFA/BmnAnM8FkMM/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":15516,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15516/richard-erickson","reputation":181,"display_name":"Richard Erickson"},"score":4,"post_id":36715,"edited":false,"creation_date":1439339862,"comment_id":61503,"body":"Check out <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galton%E2%80%93Watson_process\" rel=\"nofollow\">Galton-Watson branching process models<\/a>. They area closely related topic that focus on the probability of an individual surname going extinct."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":2,"post_id":36715,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1439398508,"comment_id":61530,"body":"In reaction to @WYSIWYG&#39;s comment: <i>The further you go in the past the smaller was the percentage of the individuals living at that time whose lineage is still alive<\/i> is very likely to be true but not necessarily indeed. However, <i>The further you go in the past the smaller (or equal) was the number of individuals living at that time whose lineage is still alive<\/i> is always true."}],"link":"http://biology