do bacteria from the cloth also attach to our hands?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Same as with the water, if the clothes do contain bacteria when you touch them your hands get contaminated! <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Or, do antibacterial substances remain on our skin and, in a sense, 'protect' us from bacteria in a given amount of time?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Unless you are talking about some specific fancy soap, the answer is NO, washing your hands with common soap will wipe out most (not all) of the bacteria from your hands but it will not give you any long-time protection against them.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45029,"question_id":45015,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-qqdVOyHI6YE/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAABM/9NDV9mIMOMQ/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":20323,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20323/alisha-sengupta","reputation":51,"display_name":"Alisha Sengupta"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461339178,"creation_date":1461339178,"body":"<p>After using soap, the pathogens that were previously present in hands are removed by the soap and water. But <strong>yes<\/strong>, bacteria from the water do <strong>attach<\/strong> themselves to our hands again, for that we should wash our hands with clean water, which may not be sterile but at least free from pathogens. Also if we wipe our hands to cloth after washing, the bacteria that may be present in the cloth adhere itself to human hands. The <strong>attachment<\/strong> of bacteria <strong>depends<\/strong> on the <strong>concentration of microbes<\/strong>, <strong><em>increase in microbial count increases the probability and risk of contamination.<\/em><\/strong> Unfortunately antibacterial soaps that use <strong>triclosan<\/strong> may kill more microorganisms while washing hands, but then they can't \"protect us\" from bacteria for some longer periods of time. Also it has been found that antibacterial soaps have the potential to create antibiotic-resistant bacteria, and some may even cause allergies.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45493,"question_id":45015,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45015/comments-on-experimental-result-regarding-anti-bacterial-soap","last_activity_date":1461339178,"creation_date":1460053077,"answer_count":2,"title":"Comments on Experimental result regarding Anti-Bacterial soap","body":"<p>After using soaps, we rinse our hands with water. <\/p>\n\n<p>Do bacteria from the water attach themselves to our hands again?<\/p>\n\n<p>If we wipe our hands to cloth after washing our hands, do bacteria from the cloth also attach to our hands?<\/p>\n\n<p>Or, do antibacterial substances remain on our skin and, in a sense, 'protect' us from bacteria in a given amount of time?<\/p>\n","question_id":45015,"tags":["microbiology","bacteriology","hygiene"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":33,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f78cdcd88b74e6ac07c168b8cefb330d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20722,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20722/city7lights","reputation":138,"display_name":"city7lights","accept_rate":62},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45490/function-of-prostate-gland-and-seminal-vesicles","last_activity_date":1461335391,"creation_date":1461335391,"answer_count":0,"title":"Function of prostate gland and seminal vesicles","body":"<p>Multiple sources (my textbook, internet, videos) have been confusing me as they state various things.<\/p>\n\n<p>Which structure produces most of the semen and produces carbohydrates for the sperm; the seminal vesicles, or the prostate gland? <\/p>\n\n<p>(<em>my textbook states that it is the prostate gland, but <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/sex-relationships/guide/male-reproductive-system?page=2\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.webmd.com/sex-relationships/guide/male-reproductive-system