 a wild type allele (+) of a gene, then in a diploid carrying one copy of each allele: m/+, if the diploid has a mutant phenotype then we would say that the m allele is dominant to the wild type allele.  If, on the other hand the m/+ heterozygote has a wild type phenotype, we would say that the m allele is recessive to the wild type allele.  You could also say that the wild type allele is dominant to the mutant allele, it is the same difference. I don&#39;t understand how the numbers show dominance of A over B."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45467/dominant-model-disease-snp","last_activity_date":1461256925,"creation_date":1461256925,"answer_count":0,"title":"Dominant model Disease SNP","body":"<p>Say that you have genotyped a SNP in a case control setting, and get the following result<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>      AA  AB  BB\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Cases      17  51  29 <\/p>\n\n<p>Controls   39  44  20<\/p>\n\n<p>where A and B are the two alleles at the locus.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thereafter you assume that the A-allele is domiant, so that the new table is<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>       AA+AB  BB\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Cases      68     29<br/>\nControls   83     20<\/p>\n\n<p>What exactly does \"dominant\" mean? Normally AB and AA would have the same trait, but what does it mean in our case? Do they have some other trait, where AB and AA give the same trait, that is possibly related to the sickness?  <\/p>\n","question_id":45467,"tags":["genetics","snp"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":17,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f78cdcd88b74e6ac07c168b8cefb330d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20722,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20722/city7lights","reputation":138,"display_name":"city7lights","accept_rate":62},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ay2bH.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22057,"link":"http:/