:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>which pigment would work best? I'm thinking food coloring (likely non toxic), methylene blue (strong staining properties), ...<\/li>\n<li>which plant / type of plant would work best? I'm thinking succulents, for their water retaining capabilities (and some species have slightly transparent leafs)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Envisioned methods:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>using a syringe to directly inject it into the leafs (this will likely not get the pigment into the cells, thus not retain it for a ling time)<\/li>\n<li>watering the plant with colored water (the pigment will probably never get absorbed by the roots)<\/li>\n<li>mix the pigment with the soil in high concentration<\/li>\n<li>inject the pigment into the xylem through an incision in the stem<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":45425,"tags":["botany","pigmentation","diy-biology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":16,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1461208307},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5c481f5545c1d2d23ce6a5b37ec2911f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":23363,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23363/user23363","reputation":6,"display_name":"user23363"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c795cf365d43a98ce4919124f839be00?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23211,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23211/thegreenone","reputation":145,"display_name":"TheGreenOne"},"score":1,"post_id":45428,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461197895,"comment_id":79549,"body":"TO be honest: I think it is practically impossible to get the species of this butterfly just by this picture as the picture itself is pretty low quality (in my opinion) and there are thousands of butterflys often only with minor differences. I would suggest you to cut the butterfly out of the picture and do a google images research. What comes out is something like a monarch butterfly 