 <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homologous_chromosome\" rel=\"nofollow\">homologous chromosomes<\/a> (except in the case of XY pair) and not <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sister_chromatids\" rel=\"nofollow\">sister chromatids<\/a>. Sister chromatids refer to the exact duplicate daughter chromosomes produced after DNA replication during mitosis.<\/p>\n\n<p>After mitosis each cell receives a copy of all the pairs of homologous chromosomes.<\/p>\n\n<p>I hope your doubt is clear now.<\/p>\n","answer_id":44466,"question_id":44464,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44464/maintenance-of-diploid-chromosome-number-at-mitosis","last_activity_date":1461207044,"creation_date":1458530411,"answer_count":1,"title":"Maintenance of Diploid chromosome number at mitosis","body":"<p>I'm just not understanding this:<\/p>\n\n<p>A regular human cell is diploid - because it has 46 chromosomes, in 23 pairs. So that means that when the cell undergoes mitosis, it will still have the full chromosome with the two sister chromatids. What is it doing in interphase when it produces the other chromosome or whatever?<\/p>\n\n<p>I thought that the sister chromatids were pulled apart, and in interphase, the single sister chromatid grew another one. However, how is this possible if a human diploid cell contains 23 pairs of 2 chromosomes each????<\/p>\n","question_id":44464,"tags":["cell-biology","chromosome"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":43,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1458612748},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b00c839c9e28eb73aeb299bf3ef69a76?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17118,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17118/shanzhengyang","reputation":166,"display_name":"ShanZhengYang","accept_rate":86},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c795cf365d43a98ce4919124f839be00?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_typ