d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14946,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14946/mdperry","reputation":2645,"display_name":"mdperry"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461202600,"creation_date":1461202600,"body":"<p>The primary product of protein coding genes are mRNAs.  When we talk about measuring gene expression we want to assay the steady-state levels of a specific mRNA within a cell.  This is usually accomplished by starting with a large number of cells and harvesting all of the mRNAs from all of the cells.  One way to measure the expression level of just one gene's mRNA is to perform a Northern Blot.  Other sensitive methods include: an S1 nuclease protection assay, an RNAse protection assay, and a primer extension assay.<\/p>\n\n<p>Microarrays have also been used extensively to measure expression levels of thousands of genes at the same time in a single experiment.<\/p>\n\n<p>With the advent of RNA-Seq methodology it is possible to count the number of transcripts in an experiment (if you have a sequenced reference genome)<\/p>\n","answer_id":45431,"question_id":45426,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45426/how-do-biologists-quantify-gene-expression-in-experiments","last_activity_date":1461202600,"creation_date":1461195220,"answer_count":2,"title":"How do biologists quantify \"gene expression\" in experiments?","body":"<p>I've read papers which contain statements such as \"control of gene expression is critical in biological processes\". <\/p>\n\n<p>How exactly does one quantify \"gene expression\"? Isn't gene expression an umbrella term describing all of the mechanism by which DNA is synthesized into an organism's phenotype? <\/p>\n","question_id":45426,"tags":["genetics","gene-expression","genomics","gene"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":45431,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":33,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2129af4f24ea78a817ab2b95f915d6f8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6624/l0r3nz4cc10","reputation":133,"display_name":"l0r3nz4cc10"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/15894a0d103ab92a2cd3b1000efca418?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6422,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6422/cornelius","reputation":6008,"display_name":"Cornelius"},"score":0,"post_id":17183,"edited":false,"creation_date":1399371763,"comment_id":23365,"body":"It is a vestigial reflex: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goose_bumps\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goose_bumps<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1HuAu.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6314,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6314/doctor-whom","reputation":876,"display_name":"Doctor Whom"},"score":7,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1399533478,"creation_date":1399533478,"body":"<p>Interesting!  I haven't seen anyone able to do this deliberately.<\/p>\n\n<p>Goose bumps are caused by the tiny muscles at the base of hair follicles contracting, and the hair stands up.  The skin around it puckers.  It's mediated by the sympathetic nervous system (the \"fight-or-flight\" aspect of the system).  This is how animals' fur stands up when afraid or upset (think of a scared cat).<\/p>\n\n<p>It's called the pilomotor reflex.  It also helps them keep warm (fur insulates) - so it happens when we're cold too.  But since we have so few hairs, it's not very useful to us. It's more of a vestigial reflex than anything.<\/p>\n\n<p>It happens for other reasons too.  See the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goose_bumps#Anatomy_and_biology\">wikipedia article,<\/a> it's a good place to start.  For more info, look <a href=\"http://www.personal.psu.edu/afr3/blogs/SIOW/2011/10/what-are-goosebumps.html\">at this article<\/a> or a medical textbook.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you can do it at will, you likely are in tune fairly well with your sympathetic nervous system.  That's excellent.  You may be able to make minor alterations in your pulse and blood pressure through breathing regulation - check out the concept of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biofeedback\">biofeedback<\/a>.  It is a way to help manage stress, keep yourself calm in terrible situations, manage anxiety or panic disorders, anger management..... <\/p>\n\n<p>Being able to use physical self-awareness to affect physiological changes takes practice to develop as a skill.  You've got a great start!<\/p>\n","answer_id":17242,"question_id":17183,"up_vote_count":7}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17183/getting-goosebumps-at-will","last_activity_date":1461202073,"creation_date":1399365134,"answer_count":1,"title":"Getting goosebumps at will","body":"<p>I can get goosebumps at will, regardless of the environment. Its mostly visible on my arms, and I can feel it on my head. It requires some level of concentration to achieve this.<\/p>\n\n<p>My questions are : what biological mechanisms are involved in doing this ? Is it common ? Is it useful ?<\/p>\n","question_id":17183,"tags":["human-biology"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":17242,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":366,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7258cbf9bfcfd112bb90d1e55f8dd1a7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19468,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19468/rha","reputation":316,"display_name":"RHA"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":3,"post_id":43759,"edited":false,"c